<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06318110 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06318110 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  A Kentucky mine operator is closing the site of one of the nation's worst coaldisasters. Arch Mineral Corp. shut down the Oven Fork Mine -- formerly knownas the Scotia Mine -- on Tuesday, laying off nearly 400 workers. The companysaid that it was too hard to get coal out of the seams and that a downturn inthe market had made the operation unprofitable. A total of 41 men have died inthe mine since it opened in 1962.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  HARD TIMES SHUT DOWN MINE THAT KILLED 41  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  National News in Brief  </MEMO><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911113  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  November  </MONTH><PG.COL>  6A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  84  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday, November 13, 199100318110,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>